Rating: 4
This was the second time we made this dish and this time we made a few changes. For the Thanksgiving season, we added dried cranberries. Also we found that leaving the peel on the pears did't adversely affect the final product and saved us some work.

Rating: 3
This dish was a big hit with my family. I made it with some changes, based on previous reviews. I used half the maple syrup and sugar that were called for in the recipe. I used whole wheat pastry flour in the topping and I used dried cranberries instead of raisens.

Rating: 2
The fruit filling was jaw achingly sweet and lets face it, good as they are, pears don't have an intense flavor. I would suggest using perfectly ripe fruit as firm pears do not get any softer with 30 min of baking time. I baked for an additional ten min and that one very firm pear nearly ruined the dish, in my estimation.

Rating: 2
This was a tasty dessert, but VERY sweet and VERY rich. If that's what you're looking for, then this is your thing. Personally, I like my fruit desserts to really taste of fruit, but found that the sugar and the maple, and even the walnut, really control this dish. I added extra ginger and traded raisins for cranberries. I might try it again with less sugar and syrup...will report back if I do.

Rating: 4
